   <abstract>This dissertation argues that Western genre films were not always concerned with issues of masculinity; and in some ways, the western and other traditionally masculine genres, were co-opted by aging actresses as a vehicle for representation. This film cycle of women-centered westerns reimagines and hybridizes the genre while questioning post-war stereotypes. From 1950 to 1959 Hollywood released 746 westerns and women received first billing in 46 of them. During a period in which aging actresses were dismissed as "has-beens," the western became a haven for the mature woman over 40. The new more mature women of the west were single, childless, owned business and property. They took risks leaving big cities for frontier towns and unlike their counterparts in male-dominated westerns, they are not supporting characters, nor working traditional feminine occupations. The women-driven western represents the dual nature of the 1950s woman, images of the happy homemaker and the working professional reflected the characters in the films. Women-driven westerns were advertised as genre hybrids, changing the way audiences viewed the western genre and its familiar conventions. Combining romantic comedy and the western, or melodrama and the western allows the exploration of gender's transformative effect on genre, gender as performance, and cultural influences on film.</abstract>
